{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505000","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505000"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:24:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:24:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2395"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2395","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2395"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.25,0.63,0.08,0.02,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2395"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90722"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2395","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2395"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2395"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74866"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1267"},{"type":"tags","id":"3390"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1598"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4580"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90722","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90722"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously well 60-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two day history of worsening upper abdominal pain, with associated nausea and vomiting. She does not take any regular medications, is a non-smoker and drinks about three glasses of wine a week. She is in obvious distress and pain. Her blood pressure is 124/80 mmHg, pulse 90/min, temperature 37.9 \u2103, respiratory rate 18/min and oxygen saturation 99% on room air. There is a visibly yellow tinge to her sclera. Her abdomen is not distended but there is tenderness in the right upper quadrant. There is no hepatosplenomegaly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer laboratory investigations are unremarkable apart from a raised white cell count, raised alkaline phosphatase and direct bilirubin. An abdominal ultrasound shows dilated intrahepatic and extrahepatic bile ducts and multiple hyperechoic spheres within the gallbladder. Intravenous antibiotics and fluid resuscitation is started. Two hours later and after one litre of isotonic saline her blood pressure is 125/80 mmHg, pulse 90/min and temperature 38.0 \u2103.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Laparoscopic cholecystectomy","Endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography (ERCP)","Magnetic retrograde cholangiopancreatography (MRCP)","Open cholecystectomy","Percutaneous cholecystostomy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has cholangitis and appears to be haemodynamically stable. She has presented with Charcot\u2019s triad - fever, jaundice and right upper quadrant pain. There is also leukocytosis and elevated markers of cholestasis i.e. raised ALP and direct bilirubin. Her ultrasound confirms the presence of gallstones and a dilated biliary system.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe does not need any urgent intervention. Whilst she has a fever, she does appear to be haemodynamically stable and a prompt \u003Cstrong\u003EERCP\u003C/strong\u003E would be the treatment of choice to decompress the biliary system. In relatively mild cases, after clinical improvement, further management would involve an \u003Cstrong\u003EMRCP\u003C/strong\u003E - providing the facilities are available. This form of imaging would provide clearer definition of the biliary system and be able to identify any obstructing elements - a likely gallstone in this case. Following this, an ERCP electively may be performed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaparoscopic cholecystectomy\u003C/strong\u003E removes potential gallstones but does not remove gallstones in the common bile duct. Moreover, this procedure is risky in septic patients when less invasive means of achieving biliary drainage are available. Whilst an \u003Cstrong\u003Eopen cholecystectomy\u003C/strong\u003E might give easier access to the biliary tree, an ERCP is a safer initial approach, with less morbidity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPercutaneous cholecystostomy\u003C/strong\u003E is an image-guided placement of drainage catheter into the gallbladder lumen, mainly for patients with acute cholecystitis for whom urgent surgery is not thought appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["MRCP is a non-invasive procedure which provides good definition of the biliary tree.","An ERCP is the preferred procedure in a septic patient and common bile duct stones"],"references":["Coelho-Prabhu N, Shah ND, Van Houten H, et al. Endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography: utilisation and outcomes in a 10-year population-based cohort. BMJ Open 2013; 3.","Mosler P. Diagnosis and management of acute cholangitis. Curr Gastroenterol Rep 2011; 13:166."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74866"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2395"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74866","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74866"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-14T15:21:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-14T15:21:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2395"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90722"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attrib